				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Advice about AA<a name="11117"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 19 03 1:27 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>There's always a lot of debate about this issue.  As I stated on a similiar thread I leveled to 60, then got 6 aa for my baron tag (lol yipee!) then leveled straight to 65 before returning to aa xp.  If I were going back to do all over again...I would xp to 65 before even getting 1 aa.  It's a matter of what you like to do with your bard.  Everyone says yeah get runspeed3...ok RS3 is nice to have, but if you are not in dungeons normally, who cares? lol.  Someone mentioned Fading Memories is the best aa for bards in the game...why?  Maybe if you spend all your time soloing.  It has its uses (albeit limited) but when it costs 800 or 900 mana to use, you're not using it much!  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-3.gif" border="0" alt="Scared" hspace="2" /> 
<br />
As a raid bard, it was more important to me to get my levels first so I could use the better songs (not to mention you get hit less and for less damage as you level up, which is huge in PoP).  Once I got 65, my first concentration in the archtype was natural durability and a combat stability (more health, less damage).  At class level, it was all about IM3 (much more beneficial than SM IMHO).  Once I capped out IM and SM I did some extended notes to help on ae songs at raids, then immediately went into innate stam and advanced inate stam.  Right there was 30 aa's but well worth it as a raid bard (I'm at 6992 hp when buffed, 4490 without).  Honestly I still have yet to do Fading Memories and I have over 100 AA.  Like I said, it's a matter of what type of bard you are primarily (solo, group or raid).</span></td>
